    <body>
      <div xml:id="KT341-kilavi">
        <p type="edition">paruvavaraviṉkaṇ vēṟupaṭum eṉak kavaṉṟa tōḻikkuk kiḻatti uraittatu. </p>


        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">Told by HER to the confidante who was anxious she would
          change at the coming of the season. </p>
      </div>

      <div xml:id="KT341">
        <lg type="edition">
          <l> palvī paṭṭa pacunaṉaik kuravam</l>
          <l> porippūm puṉkoṭu poḻilaṇik koḷāac</l>
          <l> ciṉaiyiṉi tākiya kālaiyuṅ kātalar</l>
          <l> pēṇā rāyiṉum periyōr neñcattuk</l>
          <l> kaṇṇiya vāṇmai kaṭava taṉṟeṉa</l>
          <l> valiyā neñcam valippa</l>
          <l> vāḻvēṉ ṟōḻiyeṉ vaṉka ṇāṉē.</l>


        </lg>

        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
          <l rend="indent">Even if [my] lover won't esteem [me],</l>
          <l rend="indent2">also at a time become pleasant with twigs,</l>
          <l rend="indent2">taken <note place="foot"> <term xml:lang="ta"> poḻil aṇi koḷāa </term>: for a related expression cf. KT 22.3: <term xml:lang="ta"> cilampu aṇi koṇṭa </term>, so we clearly have to read this form as positive and <term xml:lang="ta"> peyareccam</term>. </note> for decoration by the grove, of the Kuravam tree</l>
          <l rend="indent2">with green buds from which many blossoms have come forth,</l>
          <l rend="indent2">together with the Puṉku tree with parched flowers <note place="foot"> <term xml:lang="ta">  pori pū </term>: T.V.G. explains this slightly strange phrase as flowers which become puffed up like roasted rice corns.</note> ,</l>
          <l>I will live, friend, by my strength</l>
          <l rend="indent">to compel the heart which is not compelled:</l>
          <l rend="indent2">“the courage purposed by the heart of the great one is not duty” <note place="foot"> Is this supposed to mean HE did not have a good reason to leave HER, and she does not forgive him? </note> </l>


        </lg>
      </div>
    </body>
